      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A nation's right to sovereignty is the fundamental legal and moral authority to determine who enters its territory, a principle that supersedes humanitarian concerns when those concerns threaten the state's existence. Just as a country has the inherent right to defend itself against foreign aggression, it possesses an equal and non-negotiable right to control its borders to maintain political stability and national security. Any argument suggesting otherwise is a surrender of self-determination that prioritizes abstract ideals over the concrete rights of citizens to live under a functioning government.",
      "source": "target",
